Acute onset of headache, aura of scintillating scotoma, sensory disturbance (e.g., paresthesia) and vomiting are most often caused by Migraine with Aura.
Transient monocular visual disturbance (scotoma), paresthesia, and headache may represent ophthalmic artery insufficiency, also termed \amaurosis fugax\.

Posterior reversible encephalopathy syndrome (PRES) often causes headache and seizures but has also be reported to produce headache with scotomas and vomiting.  It is an important diagnosis since prompt initiation of BP medications and anticonvulsants can reverse this condition.

Headache, parasthesia, vomiting and visual symptoms in a patient with fever and rash and/or swollen eyelids and mouth could represent toxic or allergic reactions.
Other diagnostic considerations could include: transient loss of blood supply to the temporal or basilar arteries leading to transient headache and brainstem dysfunction (headache may not always accompany such events), cerebral venous sinus thrombosis (scotoma in this circumstance would have other characteristic features and other neurologic dysfunction), meningeal irritation (such as in menigitis), intracranial space occupying lesion (rare and would present with additional signs and symptoms)
Additional diagnoses should be pursued and ruled out based on history and examination.
